2. Purpose

Define an enterprise IAM design for AWS that enforces least privilege, secure user access, auditable change management, and safe delegation of permissions for services and humans.

â¸»

3. Scope
	â€¢	Human users (developers, ops, auditors)
	â€¢	Groups (role-based collections)
	â€¢	Policies (managed & inline) and permission boundaries
	â€¢	Roles for services and cross-account access
	â€¢	Access methods: console, programmatic (access keys), federation (SSO/OIDC/SAML)

â¸»

4. Design Principles
	â€¢	Least Privilege â€” grant only required permissions.
	â€¢	Roles > Users â€” prefer IAM Roles (assume-role) for services and temporary elevation.
	â€¢	Separation of Duties â€” separate admins from users; restrict who can manage IAM.
	â€¢	No long-lived credentials â€” minimize/rotate access keys, prefer SSO/federation.
	â€¢	MFA everywhere â€” require MFA for console + sensitive actions.
	â€¢	Permission Boundaries & SCPs â€” use boundaries/SCPs to limit scope.
	â€¢	Centralized Audit & Alerting â€” CloudTrail, Config, Access Analyzer, CloudWatch.
	â€¢	Automation & IaC â€” create/manage IAM via Terraform/CI pipelines.

â¸»

5. Architecture Overview

(Insert diagram: Identity Source (IdP/AD/SSO) â†’ AWS SSO/Federation â†’ IAM Roles / IAM Users â†’ Groups / Policies â†’ AWS Resources. Show cross-account roles and service roles.)

Key pieces:
	â€¢	Identity Provider (IdP) (Okta/Azure AD/Google Workspace) for centralized SSO/federation.
	â€¢	AWS SSO (IAM Identity Center) or SAML integration for human access.
	â€¢	IAM Roles for EC2/ECS/Lambda with least privilege attached.
	â€¢	IAM Users only for service accounts that truly need long-term credentials (avoid if possible).
	â€¢	Groups to aggregate permissions by job function (e.g., Dev, Infra, Security, Auditors).

â¸»

6. Recommended Logical Model
	1.	Identity Source
	â€¢	Prefer external IdP + AWS SSO. If not available, use IAM users temporarily.
	2.	Groups
	â€¢	Job-function groups: devs, infra-ops, db-admins, sec-audit.
	â€¢	Groups hold managed policies only (no inline unless necessary).
	3.	Roles
	â€¢	service-* roles for compute with attached least-privilege policies.
	â€¢	cross-account-* roles with restricted trust policies (specific Principals).
	4.	Policies
	â€¢	Use customer-managed policies scoped tightly; name with purpose (e.g., policy/ecs-s3-read-only).
	â€¢	Use aws_iam_policy_document to generate granular JSON in IaC.
	5.	Permission Boundaries
	â€¢	Apply to admin/developer accounts to prevent escalation beyond allowed set.
	6.	Admin Separation
	â€¢	Minimal set of IAM administrators; require MFA + permission boundary to limit blast radius.

â¸»

7. Controls & Monitoring
	â€¢	CloudTrail: all API activity (immutable retention policy).
	â€¢	AWS Config: rules for IAM password policy, root usage, unused keys, MFA.
	â€¢	IAM Access Analyzer: detect resources shared with external principals.
	â€¢	CloudWatch Alarms: notify on suspicious activity (e.g., CreateAccessKey by unexpected principals).
	â€¢	Periodic Review: quarterly access review; remove inactive users & keys.

â¸»

8. Risks & Mitigations
Risk
Impact
Mitigation
Compromised keys
High
Rotate keys, use short-lived credentials, SSO/federation
Over-privileged users
High
Least privilege policy, regular reviews, permission boundaries
Misconfigured trust policy
High
Strict trust conditions, automated policy linting
Root account misuse
Critical
Store root credentials offline, enable MFA, restrict root usage



Add to Section 2. Purpose / 3. Scope
	â€¢	Our AWS account does not directly manage IAM users.
	â€¢	The identity source is configured as an external IdP (e.g., Azure AD/Okta).
	â€¢	Any new user creation or attribute updates (e.g., email, group assignment) must be done in the IdP.
	â€¢	AWS IAM roles & permission sets are mapped to groups from the IdP.

